description: Ursula von der Leyen and Donald Trump reached an agreement imposing a 15% tariff on most European products imported to the US. The 27 EU member states also committed to purchasing more American oil and gas, and to investing in the country.

Israel slightly eases its grip on Gaza
description: Israel announced a suspension of its operations during daytime hours in three areas of the Gaza Strip. According to the Israeli military, 120 trucks carrying aid entered the territory on Sunday – a figure far below the 600 vehicles that entered daily before the war.

headline: France's Maxime Grousset crowned world champion in 50m fly
description: The French swimmer became world champion in the event on Sunday for the first time in his career. One year after a disappointing Olympic Games, this victory bodes well for the rest of his week at the World Aquatics Championships in Singapore.

description: Israel's ground offensive has caused massive destruction in the Gaza Strip. Recent satellite photos show that the Israeli military has nearly completely razed the second-largest city in the Palestinian enclave.

Is there a genocide in Gaza? Why legal experts are split
description: Genocide, as defined by the 1948 convention, requires both certain criminal acts to be committed and genocidal intent. While the requisite acts have been proven in Gaza, legal scholars are divided over the intent. South Africa has filed a genocide complaint against Israel with the International Court of Justice in The Hague.

headline: From AI to the military, the expansion of tech oligarchs' empires
description: 'Tech Oligarchs' (6/6). As international tensions mount, Donald Trump's second term has opened the floodgates to a rapid rapprochement between Silicon Valley giants and the US military.
byline: Damien Leloup,  Alexandre Piquard and  Raphaëlle Bacqué

headline: France's Gergovie plateau continues to reveal its ancient secrets
description: After four years exploring the depths of this archeological site in central France, archeologists have begun to draw their first conclusions, particularly regarding the so-called 'craftsmen's quarter.' This is the fourth excavation campaign at Gergovie since 1861, a site that once hosted the capital of the Arverni people.
